sentences.sentence: -- Seven Egyptian Peacekeepers to be Honored Posthumously at Ceremony -- UN Headquarters will observe the International Day of United Nations Peacekeepers and mark the 75th anniversary of UN Peacekeeping on Thursday, 25 May.

In 1948, the historic decision was made to deploy military observers to the Middle East to supervise the implementation of Israel-Arab Armistice Agreements, in what became the United Nations Truce Supervision Organization.
Since that time, more than two million peacekeepers from 125 countries have since served in 71 operations around the world.
Today, 87,000 women and men are serving in 12 conflict zones across Africa, Asia, Europe, and the Middle East.
Egypt is the 6th largest contributor of uniformed personnel to UN Peacekeeping.

It currently deploys more than 2,800 military and police personnel to the UN peace operations in Abyei, the Central African Republic, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Mali, South Sudan, and the Western Sahara.
During formal ceremonies at United Nations Headquarters, Secretary-General, António Guterres, will lay a wreath to honour the more than 4,200 UN peacekeepers who have lost their lives since 1948.

He will also preside over a ceremony in the General Assembly Hall at which Dag Hammarskjöld Medals will be awarded posthumously to 103 military, police, and civilian peacekeepers, who lost their lives serving under the UN flag last year.

Among the peacekeepers to be honoured posthumously with the Dag Hammarskjold medal are seven from Egypt: Private Mohammed Sobhy BASSIOUNI, Private Samir Ahmed MOATAZ, CPT Sameh Elsayed Mousa ABDELGAWAD, SGT Baheer Abdelgalil Abdelaziz SHERIF, CPL Elsayed Ibrahim Ahmed MOHAMED, SGT Hamza Ali Ahmed AHMED ELSAYED, Private Sayed Sawy Mohamed SHAWKY who all served with UN Multidimensional Integrated Stabilization Mission in Mali (MINUSMA).
